An example of an oath taken by lawyers in some jurisdictions, known as the &quot;Lawyer&#x27;s Oath&quot; or &quot;Attorney Oath,&quot; might include language such as:

&quot;I do solemnly swear (or affirm) that I will support the Constitution of the United States and the Constitution of the State of [State], and that I will faithfully discharge the duties of the office of attorney and counselor at law to the best of my knowledge and ability.&quot;

Similar oaths may exist for judges, which typically include a commitment to uphold the law and administer justice fairly and impartially.

Spinoza&#x27;s &quot;Ethics&quot; is divided into five parts, and his discussion of love is found in Part 3, Proposition 13. Here is the full proposition, along with the preceding axioms and the conclusion:

**Proposition 13**: &quot;By love, I mean pleasure accompanied by the idea of an external cause.&quot;

**Axiom 1**: &quot;He who loves God cannot strive that God should love him in return.&quot;

**Axiom 2**: &quot;He who has a true idea, simultaneously knows that he has a true idea, and cannot doubt of the truth of the thing perceived.&quot;

**Conclusion**: From these propositions and axioms, it follows that we can attain to the state of mind wherein we are never disappointed.
